SUMMARY:Sound Judgment in an Age of Uncertainty
DESCRIPTION:Can wisdom be cultivated?  \nWe recognise it when we see it: an elder’s timely advice\, a leader’s restraint\, a friend who asks the right question at the right moment. But knowing wisdom is not the same as knowing how to become wise. \nCognitive researcher Igor Grossmann argues that wisdom has two engines: the mental faculties behind sound judgement\, and the cultural tools\, such as proverbs\, stories\, and role models\, that sharpen them. The first engine runs on self-distance: the ability to step back from your own thinking\, sit with what you do not know\, and hold competing perspectives before acting. The second reminds us that no one becomes wise alone. \nWisdom is afterall\, a practice. Not a righteous result of age or experience. \nThe talk will then open to the audience for questions. \n
URL:https://bangaloreinternationalcentre.org/event/sound-judgment-in-an-age-of-uncertainty/
LOCATION:Bangalore International Centre\, 7\, 4th Main Road\, Domlur II Stage\, Bangalore\, Karnataka\, 560071\, India
CATEGORIES:Public Health,Science,Society
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://bangaloreinternationalcentre.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Thumbnail-37.jpg
END:VEVENT
